"""
mkt-christ commentary -- Jeremiah chapters 1-3
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-jeremiah-1-3.py

Christological focus per chapter:
  Ch1: The call narrative as prophetic-office typology; Christ as the final Prophet
    (Heb 1:1-2); prenatal calling; commission to the nations; fortified city.
  Ch2: The covenant-lawsuit against Israel; Christ as the spring of living water
    (John 4:10-14; 7:37-38); true vine (John 15); faithful one replacing the
    unfaithful spouse; prophet-killing pattern (Matt 23:37).
  Ch3: Divine Husband calling back the adulterous wife; Christ as Bridegroom-Redeemer
    (Eph 5:25-32); Good Shepherd (John 10:11); ark replaced by Christ's body
    (John 2:19-21); Jerusalem as throne of the Lamb (Rev 22:3).

mkt-christ requires an entry for every verse — brief entries for transitional verses,
substantive entries where Christological content is explicit.
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(layer, book):
    p = ROOT / "data" / "commentary" / f"mkt-{layer}" / f"{book}.json"
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(layer, book, data):
    p = ROOT / "data" / "commentary" / f"mkt-{layer}" / f"{book}.json"
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f"  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}")

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    # Never overwrite existing entries — safe to re-run
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

JEREMIAH = {
  "1": {
    "1": "<p>The book opens with a title that names Jeremiah as \"son of Hilkiah, of the priests in Anathoth.\" Anathoth was a Levitical city in Benjamin (Josh 21:18), where Abiathar the priest had been exiled by Solomon (1 Kings 2:26-27). The priestly lineage ties Jeremiah to the Mosaic-Levitical covenant tradition. Christologically, this lineage anticipates Jesus, who is both the fulfillment of the prophetic office and the new High Priest — the one who unlike Abiathar is not replaced but holds his priesthood permanently (Heb 7:24). The opening genealogy grounds the prophet's authority in covenant history; Christ's genealogies (Matt 1:1-17; Luke 3:23-38) ground his authority in both royal and priestly covenant lines.</p>",
    "2": "<p>\"The word of the LORD came to him in the days of Josiah\" — the prophetic reception formula marks the beginning of forty years of ministry. Josiah's reign (640-609 BCE) is the context of early Jeremianic prophecy, a period of covenant renewal under the rediscovered Torah (2 Kings 22-23). Christologically, the phrase <em>dĕḇar-YHWH</em> (word of YHWH) that \"comes\" to Jeremiah anticipates the climactic coming of the Word himself. John 1:14 reverses the formula: the Word that had been coming to prophets in words \"became flesh and tabernacled among us.\" Every prophetic reception formula in Jeremiah is a penultimate form of the ultimate coming of the Word incarnate.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The ministry spans the reigns of Jehoiakim and Zedekiah, concluding with the fall of Jerusalem in 586 BCE. The temporal frame — from covenant renewal under Josiah to exile under Zedekiah — covers the complete arc of Israel's final preexilic history. Christologically, this arc is the OT type of which the NT is the antitype: the period of prophetic warning, rejection, and judgment that concludes in the exile corresponds typologically to the period of John the Baptist and Jesus, whose warnings were similarly rejected, whose rejection led to the destruction of Jerusalem in 70 CE (Matt 24:1-2; Luke 21:20-24). The temporal frame of Jeremiah's ministry is itself a Christological type.</p>",
    "4": "<p>\"The word of the LORD came to me\" — the first-person shift signals the transition to the call narrative (vv4-19). Jeremiah is now narrator and protagonist. The personal reception of the divine word — the prophet as the chosen vessel of the <em>dĕḇar-YHWH</em> — is the OT form of what Jesus claims absolutely: \"Heaven and earth will pass away, but my words will never pass away\" (Matt 24:35). The difference is structural: Jeremiah receives the word; Jesus is the Word (John 1:1-3). The same eternal divine speech that comes to Jeremiah in a moment of historical calling is, in Christ, personally and permanently embodied.</p>",
    "5": "<p>\"Before I formed you in the womb I knew you, and before you were born I consecrated you; I appointed you a prophet to the nations.\" This verse is among the most Christologically dense in Jeremiah. The prenatal divine knowing (<em>yĕdaʿtîḵā</em>) and consecration (<em>qiddaštîḵā</em>) find their deepest fulfillment in Christ: Eph 1:4 (\"chosen in him before the foundation of the world\") and 1 Pet 1:20 (\"foreknown before the foundation of the world, but revealed in the last times for you\") apply precisely this pre-temporal divine appointment to Christ. Christ is not merely appointed to his prophetic office before birth; he exists before creation and is set apart for his redemptive mission in the eternal counsel of God. The appointment \"to the nations\" (<em>lāggôyim</em>) finds direct fulfillment in the Great Commission (Matt 28:19-20) and in Paul's self-description as apostle to the nations (Rom 1:5; Gal 1:16) — which Paul reads as his own participation in the prophetic calling that was first Christ's.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Jeremiah's objection: \"I do not know how to speak, for I am only a child (<em>naʿar</em>).\" The self-deprecation follows the pattern of Moses (Exod 4:10: \"I am not a man of words\") and Gideon (Judg 6:15: \"I am the least in my family\"). Christ makes no such objection — he is not a prophet called to a task beyond himself but the eternal Logos who is himself the divine speech. The contrast between Jeremiah's inadequacy and Christ's sufficiency is Pauline: \"Not that we are sufficient in ourselves to claim anything as coming from us, but our sufficiency is from God, who has made us sufficient to be ministers of a new covenant\" (2 Cor 3:5-6). Jeremiah's inadequacy models the insufficiency of all human agents; Christ models the sufficiency of the divine agent.</p>",
    "7": "<p>\"You shall go to everyone I send you to, and you shall speak everything I command you.\" The divine commissioning overrules Jeremiah's self-assessment. The language of sending (<em>šālaḥ</em>) is foundational to the prophetic office — the prophet is a sent one, a <em>šālûaḥ</em>. Jesus uses this same vocabulary of divine sending throughout John's Gospel to describe his own mission: \"The Father who sent me has himself commanded me what to say and what to speak\" (John 12:49); \"As the Father has sent me, so I am sending you\" (John 20:21). Jeremiah's commission is the OT model for the apostolic pattern — \"sent\" on the Father's behalf to speak the Father's words — which reaches its ultimate form in the Son's own mission.</p>",
    "8": "<p>\"Do not be afraid of them, for I am with you to rescue you.\" The <em>ʾal-tîrāʾ</em> (do not fear) formula combined with the divine presence promise (<em>kî ʾittĕḵā ʾānî</em>, \"for I am with you\") is the standard commissioning assurance of the OT (Josh 1:5, 9; Isa 41:10, 13; 43:1-5). Jesus's final words to his disciples repeat the same formula: \"Behold, I am with you always, to the end of the age\" (Matt 28:20). The divine presence that accompanied Jeremiah's prophetic ministry is the same presence Christ promises to his church — now mediated through the Spirit who is Christ's own presence (John 14:16-18). The presence-promise does not guarantee absence of opposition (as Jeremiah's bitter experience shows) but guarantees ultimate rescue (<em>nāṣal</em>).</p>",
    "9": "<p>\"The LORD reached out his hand and touched my mouth. The LORD said: See, I have placed my words in your mouth.\" The physical gesture of divine touch — YHWH's hand on Jeremiah's mouth — is the prophet-consecration act. Isaiah's lips were touched with a burning coal (Isa 6:7); Ezekiel ate the scroll (Ezek 3:1-3). The mouth becomes the conduit for the divine word. Christologically, this is the OT form of what John 1:14 expresses in reverse: rather than divine words placed in a human mouth, in Christ the divine Word becomes human flesh entire. The instrumentality of the prophet's mouth yields to the identity of the incarnate Word. Jesus does not receive words to speak; he speaks as one who has authority in himself (Matt 7:29: \"he taught as one who had authority, not as their scribes\").</p>",
    "10": "<p>\"I have appointed you this day over nations and kingdoms, to uproot and to tear down, to destroy and to demolish, to build and to plant.\" The six-infinitive commission (four of destruction, two of construction) defines the entire scope of Jeremiah's prophetic ministry. Christologically, this commission finds its ultimate fulfillment in Christ's own authority over the nations. Jesus claims \"all authority in heaven and on earth\" (Matt 28:18) — the universal scope of Jeremiah's commission but without limitation. The \"uproot and tear down\" side is fulfilled in Jesus's announcement of Jerusalem's destruction (Matt 24:1-2) and in the cross, which dismantles the old order; the \"build and plant\" side is fulfilled in the resurrection and in the new covenant community (Matt 16:18: \"I will build my church\"). Paul applies the same vocabulary to his own apostolic authority (2 Cor 10:8; 13:10), understanding his ministry as a continuation of the Jeremianic commission through participation in Christ.</p>",
    "11": "<p>\"I see a branch of an almond tree (<em>šāqēd</em>).\" The first vision — the almond branch — is paired with the divine response in v12. The almond tree (<em>šāqēd</em>) is the earliest-blooming tree of the Israeli spring, a sign that dormancy has ended and new life is beginning. In the Christological reading, the almond branch as first sign of divine watchfulness over the prophetic word anticipates Christ as the one in whom YHWH's long-dormant promises burst into fulfillment. Luke 1:26-38 presents the annunciation as the sudden, surprising arrival of the long-expected new beginning — God's own branch appearing at the appointed moment.</p>",
    "12": "<p>\"I am watching (<em>šōqēd</em>) over my word to carry it out.\" The wordplay (<em>šāqēd/šōqēd</em>) grounds the vision's meaning: YHWH's attentiveness to his own spoken word guarantees its fulfillment. This is the foundational claim of biblical prophecy and, Christologically, of the entire NT. Jesus's repeated use of <em>hina plērōthē</em> (\"so that it might be fulfilled\") and his statement \"I have not come to abolish the Law and the Prophets but to fulfill them\" (Matt 5:17) are explicit claims that YHWH's watchfulness over his word (Jer 1:12) is being enacted in his own person and ministry. Every OT prophecy that Jesus fulfills is a demonstration that YHWH has been watching over his word from the moment it was spoken.</p>",
    "13": "<p>\"I see a boiling pot with its mouth turned from the north.\" The second vision — a cauldron tipped to pour from the north — inaugurates the northern-foe motif that structures the entire book of Jeremiah. The boiling, scalding contents about to flood from the north mirror the language of divine wrath executed through historical instruments. Christologically, the judgment this cauldron represents — ultimately enacted in the Babylonian invasion — is the OT form of the eschatological judgment Jesus announces: the coming of the Son of Man (Matt 24:30-31) and the final pouring out of divine judgment (Rev 14:10; 16:1-21). The tilting cauldron is a type of the eschatological cup of wrath.</p>",
    "14": "<p>\"Disaster will break out from the north against all who live in this land.\" The divine interpretation of the boiling-pot vision establishes the northern-threat as YHWH's own action, not merely political contingency. Christologically, the announcement of coming judgment is a pattern Christ replicates and intensifies: his laments over Jerusalem (Matt 23:37-39; Luke 19:41-44) announce the coming disaster in the same posture — YHWH/Christ as both the one who judges and the one who grieves. The northern disaster that Jeremiah announces is thus the OT type of the Roman disaster of 70 CE, which Jesus announces as the fulfillment of both Jeremianic and Danielic patterns.</p>",
    "15": "<p>\"I am summoning all the peoples of the kingdoms of the north... they will each set up his throne at the entrance to the gates of Jerusalem.\" The image of foreign thrones at Jerusalem's gates represents the ultimate humiliation of the city that was to be YHWH's throne (3:17; Ps 2:6). Christologically, the thrones set up against Jerusalem anticipate the eschatological reversal in which Christ himself sits on the throne in the restored Jerusalem (Rev 22:3: \"the throne of God and of the Lamb\"). The human thrones displacing YHWH's reign in Jeremiah are the negative image of the divine throne that will ultimately displace all human thrones in the consummation.</p>",
    "16": "<p>\"I will pronounce my judgments against them for all their wickedness — they have forsaken me, burned incense to other gods, and bowed down to the works of their own hands.\" The three-fold indictment (forsaking, burning incense to other gods, bowing to human-made objects) defines covenant unfaithfulness as its core. Christologically, these three forms of apostasy are the negative context that makes Christ's covenant faithfulness intelligible. Where Israel forsook YHWH, Christ in his earthly life was absolutely faithful to the Father (John 8:29: \"I always do what pleases him\"); where Israel burned incense to other gods, Christ refused all temptation to serve another (Matt 4:8-10: \"Worship the Lord your God and serve only him\"). The indictment of Israel's covenant failure is the dark background against which Christ's covenant obedience shines.</p>",
    "17": "<p>\"Get yourself ready. Arise and speak to them everything I command you. Do not be terrified by them, or I will terrify you before them.\" The command to Jeremiah is a commissioning for conflict — the prophet must not capitulate to human fear, or YHWH's own reaction to capitulation will be more terrifying than the opponents. Jesus warns his disciples with similar urgency: \"Do not fear those who kill the body but cannot kill the soul. Rather fear him who can destroy both soul and body in hell\" (Matt 10:28). The alignment of divine and human will — Jeremiah must not let human fear override divine commission — is the OT form of Gethsemane's resolution: \"Not my will, but yours be done\" (Luke 22:42).</p>",
    "18": "<p>\"See, I have made you today a fortified city, an iron pillar, and bronze walls to stand against the whole land.\" YHWH's protective action transforms Jeremiah's weakness into divine strength. The three architectural images — fortified city (<em>ʿîr miḇṣār</em>), iron pillar (<em>ʿammûd barzél</em>), bronze walls (<em>ḥōmôt nĕḥōšet</em>) — describe a structure impervious to human assault. Christologically, Christ is himself the foundation and fortress of the new covenant community. Paul's prison letters envision the church's steadfastness as participation in Christ's own unshakeable strength (Phil 4:13; Eph 6:10-11); Peter describes Christ as the cornerstone against whom all opposition shatters (1 Pet 2:6-8). Jeremiah's individual strengthening is the type; the church's corporate strengthening in Christ is the fulfillment.</p>",
    "19": "<p>\"They will fight against you, but they will not overcome you, for I am with you to rescue you.\" The promise of v8 is now restated as the closing frame of the call narrative, creating an inclusio of divine presence and protection. The guarantee — opposition guaranteed, but ultimate rescue also guaranteed — is the pattern of the apostolic and prophetic experience throughout Scripture. Jesus promises his disciples the same paradoxical assurance: \"In the world you will have tribulation. But take heart; I have overcome the world\" (John 16:33). The \"overcoming\" that is denied to Jeremiah's opponents is the overcoming Jesus claims for himself — and through which his people share in the victory. Rev 3:21 (\"the one who conquers... as I also conquered\") makes this typological connection explicit.</p>"
  },
  "2": {
    "1": "<p>\"The word of the LORD came to me\" — the standard prophetic reception formula opening the covenant-lawsuit section (chs 2-3). This formula recurs throughout Jeremiah as the structural signal of a new divine address. Christologically, every instance of the word of YHWH coming to Jeremiah is a subordinate form of the final, definitive coming of the Word in Christ. As Hebrews 1:1-2 frames it: \"Long ago, at many times and in many ways, God spoke to our fathers by the prophets\" — each formula-instance is one of those many-times — \"but in these last days he has spoken to us by his Son.\" The repetition of the reception formula across Jeremiah's forty years underscores the accumulation of partial speech that points to the final and complete speaking in Christ.</p>",
    "2": "<p>\"I remember the devotion of your youth, the love of your bridal days — how you followed me through the wilderness.\" YHWH's covenant memory (<em>zāḵartî</em>) of the betrothal period — Israel's following YHWH through the wilderness — establishes the marriage metaphor that governs chs 2-3. Christologically, this divine remembering of covenant love finds its eschatological fulfillment in Christ as the Bridegroom who loved his bride before she existed. Eph 5:25-27 applies this pre-temporal love to Christ: \"Christ loved the church and gave himself up for her, that he might sanctify her.\" The bridal devotion that Israel failed to sustain, the church sustains through Christ's own faithfulness imputed to her. Rev 19:7-8 (\"the marriage of the Lamb has come, and his Bride has made herself ready\") is the restoration of exactly this bridal devotion, achieved through the Bridegroom's own work.</p>",
    "3": "<p>\"Israel was holy to the LORD, the firstfruits of his harvest.\" The <em>qōdeš</em> (holy, set apart) status of Israel as YHWH's <em>rēʾšît</em> (firstfruits) positions Israel as the dedicated portion belonging exclusively to YHWH. Those who consume what is dedicated to YHWH incur guilt. Christologically, Christ is himself the <em>ʾappîryon rēʾšît</em> (firstfruits) of the new creation — the resurrected firstfruit of those who have died (1 Cor 15:20, 23). Israel's firstfruits status was provisional and violated; Christ's firstfruits status is permanent and never violated. The church, in Christ, participates in his firstfruits consecration (James 1:18: \"a kind of firstfruits of his creatures\").</p>",
    "4": "<p>\"Hear the word of the LORD, O house of Jacob, all the families of Israel\" — the formal summons to the covenant lawsuit (<em>rîḇ</em>) opening. The legal address to \"house of Jacob... all the families of Israel\" encompasses the entire covenant people. Christologically, the same summons to hear the divine word reaches its most urgent form in the words of Jesus: \"Truly, truly I say to you...\" (the Johannine <em>amen amen</em>) and in the Synoptic \"He who has ears, let him hear\" (Matt 11:15; 13:9, 43). The prophetic call to hear the LORD's word is intensified in Christ because the speaker is himself the Word: to hear Christ is to hear the Father directly (John 14:9).</p>",
    "5": "<p>\"What fault did your fathers find in me, that they went so far from me, following worthless idols and becoming worthless themselves?\" The rhetorical question of the divine plaintiff invites Israel to state her charges against YHWH — the implication being that none can be produced. YHWH is faultless; Israel's abandonment is groundless. Christologically, this same groundless abandonment reaches its climactic expression in John's passion narrative: the crowds choose Barabbas over Jesus (John 18:38-40), and Pilate — echoing the divine plaintiff — can find no fault in him (John 18:38: \"I find no guilt in him at all\"). The Jeremianic covenant lawsuit is the OT form of the Johannine passion trial: the faultless one is rejected without cause.</p>",
    "6": "<p>\"They did not ask: Where is the LORD who brought us up out of Egypt, who led us through the wilderness?\" The failure to ask after YHWH — to seek him, to inquire of his presence — is the covenant violation that underlies all the others. The wilderness guidance (pillar of cloud/fire, the manna, the water from the rock) is the specific divine provision forgotten. Christologically, Paul identifies the wilderness-provision with Christ explicitly: \"all drank the same spiritual drink. For they drank from the spiritual Rock that followed them, and the Rock was Christ\" (1 Cor 10:4). Israel's failure to ask \"Where is YHWH who provided?\" is therefore a failure to seek Christ himself, who was present in the wilderness provision. The seeking that Israel failed to do is the seeking Jesus invites: \"Ask and it will be given to you; seek and you will find\" (Matt 7:7).</p>",
    "7": "<p>\"I brought you into a land of plenty, to enjoy its fruit and abundance. But when you entered, you defiled my land and made my heritage loathsome.\" The gift of the land — YHWH's inheritance given to Israel — is defiled by the very recipients. Christologically, this pattern of gift-defiled-by-recipients is the universal human story that only Christ breaks. Adam received the garden and defiled it; Israel received the land and defiled it; but Christ receives the inheritance of all creation (Ps 2:8; Heb 1:2: \"appointed the heir of all things\") and does not defile it. The defilement-of-inheritance pattern anticipates the need for a new Adam and a new Israel who will receive the inheritance faithfully — which is Christ's role (Rom 5:17-19; 1 Cor 15:45-49).</p>",
    "8": "<p>\"The priests did not ask, 'Where is the LORD?'... the prophets prophesied by Baal.\" Every appointed guardian of the covenant has failed: priests, Torah-teachers, rulers, and prophets alike. The comprehensive leadership failure creates a vacuum of faithful covenant mediation. Christologically, this vacuum is precisely what Christ fills as the new and better covenant mediator: he is simultaneously the faithful High Priest who always asks after the Father (John 11:41-42; 17:1-26), the true Prophet who speaks only what the Father has given him (John 12:49-50), and the righteous King who executes justice (Rev 19:11). Where every human covenant official failed, Christ alone fulfills all three offices — the threefold office (prophet, priest, king) is the Christological answer to the threefold institutional failure of v8.</p>",
    "9": "<p>\"Therefore I will bring charges against you again... and against your grandchildren will I bring charges.\" The intergenerational scope of the covenant lawsuit — extending through generations — is the legal form of what Paul addresses in Rom 1-3: the universal human condition of covenant violation, cumulative and intergenerational. The need for an answer to this intergenerational indictment is the need that Christ's work addresses: his obedience is credited to all generations of faith (Rom 5:18-19; Gal 3:13-14). The legal charges are answered not by human defense but by the one who takes the covenant-violation penalty himself.</p>",
    "10": "<p>\"Cross to the shores of Cyprus and look; send to Kedar and examine carefully.\" The invitation to a cross-cultural survey — from Cyprus (westernmost of the ANE) to Kedar (Arab tribes to the east) — establishes the universality of the charge: no nation has abandoned its gods. Christologically, this universal survey anticipates the NT's universal proclamation. The nations that were examined for loyalty to their false gods are the same nations to whom Christ is proclaimed as the living God (Acts 17:22-31). What the pagan nations did not do for their idols — abandon them — the church does for Christ: holds to him despite all opposition (Phil 1:27-28).</p>",
    "11": "<p>\"Has any nation changed its gods, even though they are not real gods? But my people have exchanged their glory for things that are worthless.\" The irony is cutting: pagan nations at least maintain loyalty to their non-existent gods, while Israel abandons the real and living God for nonentities. <em>kĕḇôdām</em> (their glory) — Israel has exchanged YHWH himself, who is their glory (Ps 106:20 quotes this verse directly). Christologically, Paul applies exactly this exchange to the universal human condition in Rom 1:23 (\"exchanged the glory of the immortal God for images\"), reading Jer 2:11 as the diagnosis of the universal human problem that only the revelation of Christ's glory answers (2 Cor 4:6: \"the light of the knowledge of the glory of God in the face of Jesus Christ\").</p>",
    "12": "<p>\"Be appalled at this, O heavens; shudder with great horror.\" The call for the heavens to witness and react to Israel's apostasy invokes the cosmic lawsuit of Deut 32:1 (\"Give ear, O heavens, and I will speak\"). The heavens as witnesses in the covenant lawsuit are a standard OT legal convention. Christologically, this cosmic horror at covenant violation finds its ultimate expression at the cross, where the heavens respond to the crucifixion: the midday darkness (Matt 27:45), the earthquake, and the torn veil (Matt 27:51-52). The cosmic <em>šāmmâ</em> (horror) provoked by Israel's covenant violation in Jeremiah is fulfilled and surpassed by the cosmic response to the one who bore that violation in himself.</p>",
    "13": "<p>\"My people have committed two evils: they have abandoned me, the spring of living water, and dug their own cisterns — cracked cisterns that cannot hold water.\" The most Christologically explicit verse in ch2. Jesus applies both sides of the contrast to himself in conversation with the Samaritan woman: he is the one who gives \"living water\" (<em>mayim ḥayyîm</em>) that becomes \"a spring of water welling up to eternal life\" (John 4:10-14). In John 7:37-38, Jesus stands at the Feast of Tabernacles — the water-drawing festival — and cries: \"If anyone thirsts, let him come to me and drink... out of his heart will flow rivers of living water.\" The spring of living water that Israel abandoned in Jer 2:13 is identified as Christ himself. The cracked cisterns of human religious self-sufficiency (whether idolatry or second-temple Judaism) are contrasted with the inexhaustible spring that is Christ. Rev 22:1 (\"the river of the water of life... flowing from the throne of God and of the Lamb\") is the eschatological fulfillment of Jer 2:13's positive image.</p>",
    "14": "<p>\"Is Israel a slave? Was he born into slavery? Then why has he become plunder?\" The rhetorical questions address the scandal of Israel's historical vulnerability — given her covenant status as YHWH's firstborn (Exod 4:22), why is she treated like a slave? Christologically, this paradox of the covenant son becoming a slave anticipates Phil 2:6-8 (Christ \"did not count equality with God a thing to be grasped, but... taking the form of a servant\"). The Son who should be free from slavery becomes a slave — but in Christ's case, voluntarily, for redemptive purpose. Gal 4:4-5 makes the connection explicit: God sent his Son \"born under the law, to redeem those who were under the law, so that we might receive adoption as sons.\"</p>",
    "15": "<p>\"Young lions have roared against him and growled; they have laid his land waste; his cities have been burned.\" The image of marauding lions destroying the land is the military-desolation metaphor. Christologically, the lion imagery has a double resonance in the NT: Peter warns that the devil \"prowls around like a roaring lion\" (1 Pet 5:8), using the same image for destructive opposition; but Rev 5:5 presents Christ as \"the Lion of the tribe of Judah, the Root of David\" who has conquered — reversing the imagery. The lion that destroys Israel becomes, in Christ, the Lion who defeats all enemies.</p>",
    "16": "<p>\"The people of Memphis and Tahpanhes have shaved the top of your head.\" Egypt's treatment of Judah — the head-shaving as sign of disgrace and subjugation — is the immediate geopolitical humiliation. Christologically, the head-shaving (crown-of-head dishonor) anticipates the crown of thorns placed on Christ at his passion (Matt 27:29; John 19:2-3). The dishonor inflicted on the covenant people foreshadows the dishonor inflicted on the covenant representative — except that in Christ's case, the dishonor is reversed into glory (Phil 2:9-11).</p>",
    "17": "<p>\"Have you not brought this on yourself by forsaking the LORD your God when he led you on the way?\" The rhetorical question places the responsibility for the covenant disaster squarely on Israel's own unfaithfulness — the self-caused suffering of forsaking the divine guide. Christologically, Christ embodies the reversal: rather than Israel who forsook the divine guide on \"the way,\" Christ declares himself to be \"the way\" (John 14:6) and never departs from it. The disciples who forsook Jesus at Gethsemane (Matt 26:56) re-enact the Jeremianic pattern; the resurrection reverses it, as Christ pursues and restores the scattered disciples (John 21:1-19).</p>",
    "18": "<p>\"Why go down to Egypt to drink from the waters of the Nile? Or why go to Assyria to drink from the Euphrates?\" The double question addresses Judah's political strategy of seeking alliances with the two great powers rather than trusting YHWH. Drinking from the Nile or Euphrates is political dependence dressed as wisdom. Christologically, this false seeking of foreign water is the foil to Jesus's offer at the well: \"Everyone who drinks of this water will be thirsty again, but whoever drinks of the water that I will give him will never be thirsty again\" (John 4:13-14). The choice between the Nile/Euphrates and the spring of living water is the OT form of the choice between all human resources and Christ.</p>",
    "19": "<p>\"Your own wickedness will punish you, and your turning away will rebuke you.\" The principle of intrinsic moral consequence — sin as its own punishment — is a consistent wisdom theme (Prov 1:31; 5:22). Christologically, Gal 6:7-8 (\"whatever a man sows, that he will also reap\") formulates the same principle. But the gospel's radical move is that Christ enters into the consequence of others' sowing — he who sowed only righteousness reaps the harvest of others' wickedness (Gal 3:13: \"Christ redeemed us from the curse of the law by becoming a curse for us\"). The intrinsic-consequence principle of Jer 2:19 is not negated by the cross but absorbed into it: Christ's death is the enacted consequence of humanity's turning away.</p>",
    "20": "<p>\"For long ago I broke your yoke and tore off your chains. But you said, 'I will not serve!'\" The exodus liberation — YHWH breaking Israel's yoke of slavery in Egypt — is met with refusal to serve YHWH as liberator. The paradox: freed from one yoke, Israel refuses the yoke that is the covenant. Christologically, Jesus offers a different yoke: \"Come to me, all who labor and are heavy laden, and I will give you rest. Take my yoke upon you... for my yoke is easy and my burden is light\" (Matt 11:28-30). The refusal to serve YHWH in Jer 2:20 is the form of the same rebellion against Christ's gentle yoke. The difference: the new covenant yoke is borne by the one who offers it — Christ carries his own yoke.</p>",
    "21": "<p>\"I had planted you as a choice vine (<em>śōrēq</em>), of pure and wholesome seed. How then have you turned against me into the wild shoots of a foreign vine?\" The vineyard imagery is one of the most developed Christological types in the OT. Isaiah 5:1-7 expands it into the Song of the Vineyard (the beloved's vineyard producing wild grapes). Jesus explicitly takes up this imagery in John 15:1: \"I am the true vine\" (<em>hē ampelos hē alēthine</em>), deliberately contrasting himself with the false vine of Israel's covenant failure. The choice vine planted by YHWH in Jer 2:21 but producing wild growth is answered by Christ who is himself the true vine producing true fruit. John 15:5 (\"I am the vine; you are the branches\") completes the metaphor: the restoration of Israel-as-vine happens through union with Christ-as-vine.</p>",
    "22": "<p>\"Even if you scrubbed yourself with lye and used much soap, the stain of your guilt would still be before me.\" The indelibility of moral guilt — no human cleansing agent removes the <em>māʾôr ʿăwōnēḵ</em> (stain of your iniquity) — is the diagnosis that only the cross answers. Christologically, Heb 9:13-14 contrasts the ritual purification of the Levitical system with the blood of Christ: \"How much more will the blood of Christ... purify our conscience from dead works.\" 1 John 1:7 (\"the blood of Jesus his Son cleanses us from all sin\") is the direct answer to Jer 2:22's impossible standard. The cleansing that lye and soap cannot achieve, Christ's atoning death accomplishes.</p>",
    "23": "<p>\"How can you say, 'I am not defiled, I have not chased after the Baals'?\" The self-justification that denies evident guilt — the animal imagery of the camel and wild donkey (vv23-24) developing the point — is the moral blindness that accompanies persistent sin. Christologically, this self-justification is what Jesus confronts in the Pharisees (Luke 18:9-14: the self-justifying Pharisee and the tax collector who knows his guilt) and in the rich young ruler (Matt 19:16-22: the one who claims to have kept all the commandments). The self-deception of Jer 2:23 is not merely Israel's problem but the universal human condition that the NT identifies as the prerequisite blindness to grace.</p>",
    "24": "<p>\"Like a wild donkey at home in the desert, sniffing the wind in her craving — who can hold her back when she is in heat?\" The wild donkey image for uncontrollable sexual desire applied to Israel's idolatry is a deliberately shocking metaphor for covenant unfaithfulness. The inability to hold back (<em>yiśśĕrennāh</em>, Qal imperfect, who can restrain her?) describes the compulsive quality of idolatrous desire. Christologically, Rom 1:24-27 describes exactly this compulsive, craving disorder as the consequence of idolatry: God \"gave them up to dishonorable passions\" as the judicial consequence of exchanging the Creator for the creature. The wild-donkey craving of Jer 2:24 is the OT image of what Paul diagnoses as the theological root of human sexual disorder.</p>",
    "25": "<p>\"But you said: It is hopeless! I love other gods, and after them I will go.\" The declaration of hopeless addiction to false gods — \"it is hopeless (<em>nôʾāš</em>)\" — is the voice of entrenched covenant rebellion. The despair of the one who has abandoned YHWH and cannot conceive of return is the condition Paul describes in Eph 2:12 (\"without hope and without God in the world\"). Christologically, the gospel's answer to this despairing self-assessment is the hope offered in Christ: \"You who once were far off have been brought near by the blood of Christ\" (Eph 2:13). The hopelessness of Jer 2:25 is answered not by human self-reform but by the divine initiative in the cross.</p>",
    "26": "<p>\"As a thief is put to shame when caught, so the house of Israel will be shamed — they, their kings, their officials, their priests, and their prophets.\" The comprehensive shame covering all Israel's leadership is the diagnosis that makes the new covenant's comprehensive address necessary. Christologically, the shame (<em>bōšet</em>) that covers the entire community — every official level, every institution — is what Christ absorbs at the cross (Heb 12:2: \"who for the joy set before him endured the cross, despising the shame\"). The communal shame of Jer 2:26 is answered by Christ's personal assumption of shame, and his resurrection is the reversal of that shame into glory.</p>",
    "27": "<p>\"They say to a tree, 'You are my father,' and to a stone, 'You gave me birth.' They have turned their backs to me and not their faces. Yet in the time of their trouble they will cry, 'Rise up and save us!'\" The hypocrisy is complete: YHWH is addressed only in crisis, while trees and stones receive the paternal/natal devotion that belongs to him. The crisis-prayer to YHWH after devoted loyalty to idols is the pattern Jesus addresses in Matt 7:21-23 (\"Not everyone who says to me, 'Lord, Lord,' will enter the kingdom\"). The turning of backs in normal time and faces only in trouble is the OT form of the false discipleship Christ identifies as dangerous. The authentic relationship involves facing toward God not only in crisis but continuously — which only the indwelling Spirit of the new covenant enables (John 14:17).</p>",
    "28": "<p>\"But where are the gods you made for yourself? Let them rise up, if they can rescue you in the time of your trouble.\" The challenge to idols to rise up (<em>yāqûmû</em>) and rescue is the theological polemic that frames the entire OAN tradition. Christologically, this challenge is answered by Christ's resurrection: the one YHWH raised from the dead does in fact save in the time of trouble. Acts 2:24 (\"God raised him up, loosing the pangs of death\") and Rom 10:9 (\"if you... believe in your heart that God raised him from the dead, you will be saved\") present the resurrection as the definitive answer to every \"can your god rise up and save?\" challenge in the OT. The idols cannot rise; Christ does.</p>",
    "29": "<p>\"Why do you bring a complaint against me? You have all rebelled against me.\" YHWH as the defendant in Israel's counter-suit — she accuses YHWH of injustice even as she has rebelled — is the rhetorical posture of covenant inversion. Paul addresses the same counter-accusation in Rom 9:19-21 (\"Why does he still find fault? Who can resist his will?\") and in the diatribe of Rom 2-3. The answer in both Jeremiah and Paul is the same: the charge of divine injustice is groundless because the covenant violation was entirely human. Rom 3:4 (\"Let God be true though every man be a liar\") is the Pauline form of Jer 2:29.</p>",
    "30": "<p>\"I have struck your people in vain; they accepted no correction. Your own sword has consumed your prophets like a ravaging lion.\" The killing of YHWH's prophets by Israel's own sword is the culminating indictment of v30 and is the pattern Jesus identifies as the characteristic sin of Jerusalem. Matt 23:37: \"O Jerusalem, Jerusalem, you who kill the prophets and stone those who are sent to you!\" — a direct citation of the Jeremianic pattern. Acts 7:52 (Stephen's speech) makes the same charge: \"Which of the prophets did your fathers not persecute?\" The sword that consumed the prophets in Jer 2:30 is the same sword that will be raised against Christ, the last and greatest of the sent prophets (and more than a prophet).</p>",
    "31": "<p>\"O generation, take heed of the word of the LORD: Have I been a desert to Israel or a land of thick darkness? Why do my people say, 'We are free; we will come to you no more'?\" The divine challenge — YHWH as the one who has provided, not withheld — uses the wilderness metaphor: has YHWH been <em>midbār</em> (desert, wilderness, deprivation) to Israel? The answer is no; YHWH has been the spring of living water (v13). Christologically, Jesus's claim \"I am the bread of life; whoever comes to me shall not hunger, and whoever believes in me shall never thirst\" (John 6:35) is the self-application of YHWH's challenge in Jer 2:31. The declaration \"We will come to you no more\" is the ultimate form of covenant rejection that finds its NT form in those who \"went away\" from Jesus (John 6:66).</p>",
    "32": "<p>\"Does a young woman forget her jewelry, or a bride her wedding attire? Yet my people have forgotten me — for more days than can be counted.\" The absurdity of Israel's forgetfulness — more remarkable than a bride forgetting her wedding dress — is the rhetorical vehicle for the depth of the betrayal. Christologically, this contrast between bridal devotion and Israel's forgetfulness anticipates the church's calling to undivided devotion to Christ as the bride to her husband. Paul uses the bridal imagery in 2 Cor 11:2: \"I betrothed you to one husband, to present you as a pure virgin to Christ.\" The church's forgetting of Christ would be the NT counterpart of Israel's forgetting — which is why Paul's pastoral letters constantly recall, remind, and re-present the gospel.</p>",
    "33": "<p>\"How skilled you are at pursuing love; you have become expert enough to teach the wicked your ways.\" The ironic praise of Israel's expertise in pursuing false loves — she has become a teacher of wickedness — inverts the covenant calling to be a light to the nations (Isa 49:6). Instead of teaching the nations YHWH's ways, Israel has become a curriculum in unfaithfulness. Christologically, Christ reverses this irony: where Israel taught wickedness, Christ is himself the way, truth, and life that teaches the nations (Matt 28:20: \"teaching them to observe all that I have commanded you\"). The church's vocation to teach the nations is grounded in Christ's own teaching authority, not in human expertise.</p>",
    "34": "<p>\"On your garments is found the lifeblood of innocent poor people — you did not catch them breaking in.\" The blood of innocent people — wrongfully shed outside of the self-defense exception of Exod 22:2-3 — is on Israel's hands. The shedding of innocent blood defiles the land (Num 35:33-34). Christologically, Matt 27:24-25 presents Pilate washing his hands of \"innocent blood\" (the only NT use of <em>haima athōon</em>, lit. \"innocent blood\") while the crowd accepts responsibility. Jesus is the innocent one whose blood is shed — but unlike the innocent poor of Jer 2:34, whose blood condemns those who shed it, Christ's innocent blood is the means of covenant cleansing (Heb 9:14; 1 John 1:7).</p>",
    "35": "<p>\"Yet you say, 'I am innocent; surely his anger has turned from me.' But I will bring judgment against you because you say, 'I have not sinned.'\" The refusal to acknowledge sin — the double self-justification (\"I am innocent\" and \"I have not sinned\") — is the state that makes repentance impossible. 1 John 1:8-10 directly addresses this: \"If we say we have no sin, we deceive ourselves... If we confess our sins, he is faithful and just to forgive us our sins.\" The covenant lawsuit's requirement that the defendant acknowledge guilt is the OT form of the NT's requirement of confession for forgiveness. Christ's work makes forgiveness possible; the acknowledgment of sin makes it accessible.</p>",
    "36": "<p>\"Why do you rush about so much, changing course? You will be disappointed by Egypt just as you were disappointed by Assyria.\" The political strategy of cycling through great-power alliances — Egypt to Assyria and back — is the foreign-policy form of spiritual unfaithfulness. Neither alliance saves; neither power proves reliable. Christologically, this disappointment by all human powers and alliances is the universal experience that drives the seeking of the divine king. Ps 146:3-5 (\"Put not your trust in princes... blessed is he whose help is the God of Jacob\") makes the theological application; Jesus's kingship is the one power that never disappoints (Rom 10:11: \"everyone who believes in him will not be put to shame\").</p>",
    "37": "<p>\"You will leave Egypt too with your hands on your head in defeat, for the LORD has rejected the ones you are trusting.\" The hands-on-head gesture (<em>yādêḵā ʿal-rōʾšēḵ</em>) is the posture of total humiliation and defeat (2 Sam 13:19; Tamar's grief). YHWH rejects the objects of Israel's trust — the great empires she courted — because he is the only trustworthy power. Christologically, this rejection of false trust-objects is the theological ground of Christ's exclusive claim. John 14:6 (\"No one comes to the Father except through me\") is not merely soteriological exclusivism but a statement about the trustworthiness of all other refuges: hands on heads, all of them fail. Only Christ, rejected and crucified, is vindicated by the Father and established as the sole reliable foundation (1 Pet 2:6).</p>"
  },
  "3": {
    "1": "<p>\"If a man divorces his wife and she goes and marries another, can he take her back? Would not the land be totally defiled? But you have given yourself to many lovers — yet return to me.\" The Deuteronomic divorce law (Deut 24:1-4) forbids a divorced woman's return to her first husband after she has remarried. YHWH applies this law to his own situation with Israel — then overturns it with the unexpected divine call to return. Christologically, this is the OT statement of the gospel's scandalous grace: the law says return is impossible; grace says return is invited. The \"yet return to me\" is the OT form of the prodigal son's father running to meet the returning child (Luke 15:20). Christ himself embodies the divine overturning of the law's impossibility: his atoning work makes reconciliation possible where the law says it cannot happen. Eph 5:25-27 (Christ giving himself for the church \"to present her... without spot or wrinkle\") is the fulfillment of the divine return-invitation of Jer 3:1.</p>",
    "2": "<p>\"Raise your eyes to the bare hilltops and look — is there any place you have not been violated?\" The rhetorical survey of Judah's spiritual promiscuity — every hilltop a site of covenant violation — establishes the universality of the corruption. The image of violation at every road and hilltop also evokes the vulnerability of those who travel without protection. Christologically, the comprehensive defilement of the land anticipates the comprehensive redemption Christ accomplishes — not a partial cleansing of some hilltops but a total renewal. 2 Cor 5:17 (\"the old has gone, the new has come\") and Rev 21:5 (\"I am making all things new\") are the eschatological fulfillment of the comprehensive spiritual cleansing that begins at the cross.</p>",
    "3": "<p>\"Therefore the rain has been withheld, and the spring rain has not come; yet you have a prostitute's brazenness — you refuse to be ashamed.\" The ecological consequence of covenant unfaithfulness — withheld rain — reflects the Deuteronomic blessing-and-curse structure (Deut 28:12, 23-24). The brazenness (<em>meṣaḥ ʾiššâ zônâ</em>, prostitute's forehead) in refusing to be ashamed recalls Ezek 16:30 and the stubbornness diagnosed throughout the prophetic tradition. Christologically, the withheld rain — the absence of divine blessing as consequence of rebellion — is reversed in Christ: the pouring out of the Spirit at Pentecost (Acts 2:17: \"I will pour out my Spirit on all flesh\") is the restoring of the withheld blessing. The brazenness that prevented shame is overcome by the Spirit-given repentance that produces godly sorrow (2 Cor 7:10).</p>",
    "4": "<p>\"Have you not just been calling out to me, 'My Father, you are my closest companion from my youth'?\" The address to YHWH as Father (<em>ʾāḇî</em>) and guide-from-youth is a cry of covenant intimacy invoked at moments of need — but hollow when the daily devotion belongs to idols. Christologically, Christ teaches his disciples to pray \"Our Father\" (Matt 6:9) — but the Abba-address is only authentic when grounded in covenant relationship through the Spirit (Rom 8:15-16: \"you have received the Spirit of adoption as sons, by whom we cry, 'Abba! Father!'\"'). The hollow father-address of Jer 3:4 is contrasted with the genuine Spirit-prompted father-cry that is the mark of adoption in Christ.</p>",
    "5": "<p>\"Will he be angry forever? Will he stay angry to the end? But see — you have spoken, and you have done all the evil you could.\" The question appeals to YHWH's covenantal patience — will his anger be permanent? — while the oracle simultaneously exposes the hypocrisy: the appeal to divine patience is made while continuing in evil. Christologically, this tension between appealing to divine patience and continuing in sin is precisely what Paul addresses in Rom 6:1 (\"Are we to continue in sin that grace may abound? By no means!\"). The appeal to long-suffering grace as license for continued sin is as old as Jer 3:5. Christ's atoning death is not an extension of license but a transformation of the will through the Spirit.</p>",
    "6": "<p>\"Have you seen what faithless Israel has done? She has gone up to every high mountain and under every spreading tree and committed adultery there.\" The geographic description of Israel's apostasy — high mountains and spreading trees were the standard sites of Canaanite fertility cult worship — establishes the comparison between faithless Israel (northern kingdom) and unfaithful Judah. Christologically, the adulterous Israel/Judah comparison creates the backdrop for Christ's own use of \"adulterous generation\" language (Matt 12:39; 16:4; Mark 8:38). Jesus's contemporaries who seek signs rather than faithfulness are the inheritors of the Jeremianic pattern of covenant apostasy disguised as religious activity.</p>",
    "7": "<p>\"I said, after she had done all this, 'Return to me,' but she did not return.\" The repeated divine call to return (<em>šûḇî</em>) that goes unheeded is the pattern of the parable of the wicked tenants (Matt 21:33-46): servant after servant is sent, all rejected, until finally the son is sent. The refusal to return in Jer 3:7 is the cumulative record of covenant rejection that culminates in the rejection of the Son himself. Jesus explicitly reads his own rejection as the climactic instance of this pattern (Matt 21:42: \"The stone that the builders rejected has become the cornerstone\").</p>",
    "8": "<p>\"I saw that because faithless Israel had committed adultery, I had sent her away and given her a certificate of divorce; yet her unfaithful sister Judah had no fear, but went and became a prostitute too.\" The historical sequence — Israel divorced, Judah observing and learning nothing — establishes covenant unfaithfulness as a teachable sin that spreads from the example of others. Christologically, this contagion of unfaithfulness is the opposite of the contagion of faithfulness Christ establishes. John 17:20-21 (Jesus praying for those who will believe through the disciples' word) describes the spread of covenant faithfulness through testimony — the positive antitype of Judah's learning of unfaithfulness from Israel.</p>",
    "9": "<p>\"She defiled the land by the brazen ease of her prostitution, committing adultery with stones and wooden posts.\" The material objects of idolatry — stone pillars (<em>ʾāḇen</em>) and wooden Asherah poles (<em>ʿēṣ</em>) — are the physical forms of covenant apostasy. The \"brazen ease\" (<em>qōl zenûtāh</em>, lit. the sound/noise of her prostitution) suggests the public and unembarrassed character of the cult. Christologically, John 4:23-24 addresses worship of stone and wood indirectly: \"God is spirit, and those who worship him must worship in spirit and truth.\" The stone and wooden cult objects of Jer 3:9 are the OT form of all worship misdirected away from the God who is spirit toward material replacements.</p>",
    "10": "<p>\"In spite of all this, Judah, her unfaithful sister, did not return to me with all her heart — only in pretense.\" The <em>bĕḵol-libbāh</em> standard (with all her heart) is the Shema's standard (Deut 6:5: \"love YHWH your God with all your heart\") — which Judah's return failed to meet. Half-hearted covenant return is worse than honest apostasy because it creates the appearance of faithfulness without the reality. Christologically, this whole-heart standard is what Christ fulfills in his covenant obedience (John 8:29: \"I always do what pleases him\") and what the new covenant provides through the Spirit (Jer 31:33; Ezek 36:26-27). The half-heartedness of Jer 3:10 is overcome in new covenant believers not by human effort but by divine transformation of the heart.</p>",
    "11": "<p>\"Faithless Israel has shown herself more in the right than unfaithful Judah.\" The comparative verdict — apostate Israel is more righteous than hypocritical Judah — is a moral paradox. Outright rejection of YHWH (Israel) is less culpable than pretending covenant faithfulness while living apostasy (Judah). Christologically, this is the principle Jesus applies in Matt 21:31 (\"Truly I tell you, the tax collectors and the prostitutes are entering the kingdom of God before you\") — honest sinners are closer to the kingdom than religious hypocrites, because they can hear the call to repentance. The comparative righteousness of honest apostasy over hypocritical religion is a consistent Christological principle throughout the Gospels.</p>",
    "12": "<p>\"Return, O faithless Israel... I will not look on you in anger, for I am faithful in love (<em>ḥāsîd</em>).\" The divine attribute <em>ḥāsîd</em> (one who exercises <em>ḥesed</em>, steadfast covenant loyalty) is applied to YHWH himself — the only occurrence in Jeremiah where YHWH calls himself <em>ḥāsîd</em>. The call to return grounded in divine <em>ḥesed</em> is the OT form of the gospel. Christologically, 1 John 1:9 (\"he is faithful and just to forgive us our sins\") is the NT statement of what Jer 3:12 declares: the ground of return is divine faithfulness, not human merit. Christ's atoning death is the enacted expression of the divine <em>ḥesed</em> that does not withdraw despite the depth of the covenant violation.</p>",
    "13": "<p>\"Only acknowledge your guilt — that you have rebelled against the LORD your God.\" The minimal requirement for return is honest acknowledgment of sin (<em>raq deʿî ʿăwōnēḵ</em>). This is the OT form of the NT call to confession: 1 John 1:9 (\"if we confess our sins\") and Luke 15:18 (the prodigal's prepared speech: \"I have sinned against heaven and before you\"). The simplicity of the requirement — only acknowledge — emphasizes that what blocks return is not the magnitude of the sin but the refusal to name it. Christologically, the new covenant's provision of the Spirit convicts of sin (John 16:8) precisely in order to make this acknowledgment possible.</p>",
    "14": "<p>\"Return, faithless children, declares the LORD, for I am your husband (<em>baʿaltî bāḵem</em>). I will take you, one from a city and two from a family, and bring you to Zion.\" The divine husband-claim grounds the call to return in covenant marriage. <em>ʾānoḵî bāʿaltî bāḵem</em> (I am your husband, lit. I have exercised the baal-role over you) is the covenant-marriage claim that Christ takes up in the new covenant. Eph 5:25-32 (\"husbands, love your wives, as Christ loved the church\") establishes Christ as the divine husband who fulfilled what YHWH promised in Jer 3:14. The specificity of the gathering — \"one from a city, two from a family\" — anticipates the remnant-theology that Paul develops in Rom 11:5 (\"a remnant chosen by grace\"). The gathering to Zion is fulfilled in the eschatological gathering of the church around Christ (Heb 12:22-24; Rev 14:1).</p>",
    "15": "<p>\"I will give you shepherds after my own heart, who will lead you with knowledge and wisdom.\" The promise of shepherds <em>kĕlibbî</em> (according to my heart) is one of the clearest messianic predictions in Jeremiah. The entire prophetic tradition indicts Israel's false shepherds (2:8; 10:21; 12:10; 23:1-4); the promise here is for true shepherds who embody YHWH's own pastoral character. Christologically, John 10:11 is the direct fulfillment: \"I am the good shepherd. The good shepherd lays down his life for the sheep.\" Jesus explicitly identifies himself as the shepherd \"after God's own heart\" — one whose leadership is characterized by self-giving love, not exploitation. The plural \"shepherds\" also anticipates the undershepherds of the apostolic/pastoral office (Eph 4:11; 1 Pet 5:2-4), but always derivative from and subordinate to Christ the chief Shepherd (1 Pet 5:4).</p>",
    "16": "<p>\"When you have become numerous and multiplied in the land in those days, no one will say any longer, 'The ark of the covenant of the LORD.' It will not come to mind; no one will remember it; no one will look for it; it will not be made again.\" The prophecy that the ark will be forgotten is one of the most radical statements in the OT about its own cultic structures. The ark — the central sacramental object of the Mosaic covenant, the physical dwelling-place of YHWH's presence — will be superseded. Christologically, John 2:19-21 identifies Jesus's body as the new temple (\"he was speaking about the temple of his body\"), and Heb 9:11-12 identifies Christ as the new high priest who entered \"not into a holy place made with hands... but into heaven itself.\" Rev 21:22 provides the ultimate fulfillment: \"I saw no temple in the city, for its temple is the Lord God Almighty and the Lamb.\" The ark disappears because the Lamb who was the ark's ultimate referent — the presence of YHWH dwelling with his people, the propitiation on the mercy seat (Rom 3:25) — has appeared in person.</p>",
    "17": "<p>\"At that time Jerusalem will be called the throne of the LORD, and all nations will gather to it, to honor the name of the LORD in Jerusalem; they will no longer follow the stubborn inclination of their evil hearts.\" The eschatological Jerusalem as YHWH's throne, gathering the nations, is the vision that the entire OAN collection (chs 46-51) is structured around — judgment of the nations is the negative preparation for this positive gathering. Christologically, Rev 22:3 is the fulfillment: \"the throne of God and of the Lamb will be in the city.\" The nations gathered to Jerusalem to honor YHWH's name in Jer 3:17 become in Revelation the nations gathered to the New Jerusalem to worship before the Lamb (Rev 21:24-26). The stubborn inclination of the evil heart (<em>šĕrîrût libbām hārāʿ</em>) that previously drove the nations into idolatry is overcome by the Spirit who writes the law on the heart (Jer 31:33; Ezek 36:26-27).</p>",
    "18": "<p>\"In those days the house of Judah will join the house of Israel, and together they will come from the northern land to the land I gave your ancestors.\" The reunion of the divided kingdom — north and south returning together as one people — is the foundational reunion vision of the prophetic restoration oracles (Ezek 37:15-22: the two sticks becoming one; Isa 11:13: Ephraim's jealousy ceasing). Christologically, Eph 2:14-16 applies this reunion directly to Christ's work: \"He himself is our peace, who has made us both one and has broken down in his flesh the dividing wall of hostility.\" The Jews and Gentiles who are reconciled in Christ fulfill and surpass the Israel/Judah reunification vision: the wall between the two covenantal communities is torn down by the cross, and the one new humanity replaces both.</p>",
    "19": "<p>\"I had thought, 'How gladly I would treat you as my children and give you a desirable land... I had expected you to call me My Father and never turn from me.'\" YHWH's stated desire to treat Israel as children (<em>bānîm</em>) and give them the father-relationship is the OT expression of the adoption theology that the NT fulfills in Christ. The expectation — \"I expected you to call me My Father\" — finds its fulfillment in the Lord's Prayer and in the Spirit of adoption. Gal 4:4-7 makes the connection explicit: God sent his Son \"so that we might receive adoption as sons. And because you are sons, God has sent the Spirit of his Son into our hearts, crying, 'Abba! Father!'\" The father-relationship YHWH desired but Israel failed to sustain is established in Christ and secured by the Spirit.</p>",
    "20": "<p>\"But like a woman who is unfaithful to her husband, you have been unfaithful to me, O house of Israel.\" The covenant-marriage metaphor reaches its most direct statement: Israel is the unfaithful wife, YHWH the faithful husband. Christologically, Eph 5:25-32 transposes the entire relationship: Christ is the husband who loved his wife (the church) even when she was unfaithful, to the point of giving himself up for her. The faithfulness of Christ where Israel was faithless is the Christological inversion of Jer 3:20. 2 Cor 11:2 (Paul presenting the church as a pure virgin to Christ) assumes the covenant-marriage framework and makes the point that the church's faithfulness is Christ's own gift, not human achievement.</p>",
    "21": "<p>\"A cry is heard on the bare hilltops — the weeping and pleading of the children of Israel — because they have perverted their ways and forgotten the LORD their God.\" The weeping on the hilltops is the sound of recognized ruin — the same hills where Israel committed spiritual adultery (vv2, 6) are now the sites of lamentation over its consequences. Christologically, Luke 19:41-44 presents Jesus weeping over Jerusalem on a hill (the Mount of Olives) for the same reason — the city has not recognized the time of its visitation, has perverted its ways, and will face the consequences. The divine grief at Israel's self-destruction in Jer 3:21 is embodied in Christ's own tears at Jerusalem.</p>",
    "22": "<p>\"Return, faithless children, and I will heal your faithlessness. 'Here we are — we come to you, for you are the LORD our God.'\" YHWH's offer to <em>heal</em> (<em>ʾerpāʾ</em>) the faithlessness (<em>mĕšûḇôtêḵem</em>) — not merely forgive but cure the condition — is the deepest covenant promise in the chapter. The answer from the people (vv22b-25) is the model penitential confession. Christologically, the healing of faithlessness is what Christ accomplishes through the Spirit: not external forgiveness alone but internal transformation. 1 Pet 2:24 (\"by his wounds you have been healed\") applies the healing language of Jer 3:22 to Christ's atoning work, reading the healing as both somatic and spiritual. The model confession that follows (\"here we are, we come to you\") is the structure of faith itself — the turning toward YHWH in response to the healing offer.</p>",
    "23": "<p>\"Surely the commotion on the hills and mountains is a delusion; surely in the LORD our God is the salvation of Israel.\" The confessional recognition that the hill-worship is <em>šeqer</em> (delusion, falsehood) and that salvation belongs to YHWH alone is the OT form of the NT's exclusive soteriology. Acts 4:12 (\"there is no other name under heaven given among men by which we must be saved\") is the Christological sharpening of Jer 3:23's principle. The nations' mountains and hills offer nothing; salvation is <em>lĕYHWH ʾĕlōhênû</em> (to YHWH our God) — and in the NT, to the one who is himself the name of YHWH made flesh.</p>",
    "24": "<p>\"For the shameful thing has consumed from our youth what our fathers worked for — their flocks and herds, their sons and daughters.\" The penitential confession acknowledges that idol worship (<em>Bōšet</em>, the Shame — a polemical substitute name for Baal, used in personal names: Ishbosheth, Mephibosheth) has devoured the nation's inheritance across generations. The intergenerational damage of covenant unfaithfulness — children and grandchildren affected by the sins of earlier generations — is the condition Christ enters to redeem. Matt 23:35-36 (\"so that on you may come all the righteous blood... truly I say to you, all these things will come upon this generation\") and Gal 3:13 (Christ taking the curse that accumulated across generations) together show how Christ's redemptive work addresses the generational depth of the Bōšet-consumption described in Jer 3:24.</p>",
    "25": "<p>\"Let us lie down in our shame, for our dishonor covers us; for we have sinned against the LORD our God, both we and our fathers, from our youth until today, and we have not obeyed the voice of the LORD our God.\" The closing confession of ch3 is the most comprehensive penitential statement in Jeremiah chs 1-3 — spanning from youth to present, including both current and ancestral generations, covering both active sin and failure to obey. Christologically, this is the OT model of the full confession that the gospel invites and enables. The specific elements — lying down in shame (humiliation), acknowledging dishonor (public recognition of guilt), naming specific sin (against YHWH our God), temporal scope (from youth to today), communal scope (we and our fathers), and specific failure (not obeying the divine voice) — correspond to the NT structure of genuine repentance. The new covenant's provision that makes this full confession possible is the Spirit of conviction (John 16:8) and the blood of Christ that cleanses the conscience (Heb 9:14) so that confession is not merely self-condemnation but the threshold of genuine restoration.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm("christ", "jeremiah")
    merge_comm(existing, JEREMIAH)
    save_comm("christ", "jeremiah", existing)
    total = sum(len(v) for v in existing.values())
    print(f"Jeremiah mkt-christ: {len(existing)} chapters, {total} verses total.")

if __name__ == "__main__":
    main()
